node.text: @te_ed_ yes. i was about to say. if the subject is an ilusion, then WHO is experiencing the ilusion?
It’s more than a singular experience, while also being one at the same time

Is the self a singular, unified entity, or a fragmented illusion? Is our perception of the self real, or just a fleeting construct shaped by our ever-changing minds?

Neuroscientist Sam Harris dives deep into the mysteries of consciousness and the nature of selfhood in a thought-provoking debate with physicist Roger Penrose and neuroscientist Sophie Scott.

Tap the link in bio to watch.
It’s more than a singular experience, while also being one at the same time
@te_ed_ Cogito ergo sum
@te_ed_ yes. i was about to say. if the subject is an ilusion, then WHO is experiencing the ilusion?

You cannot consistently doubt or deny the self because the self is a prerequisite for doing any of that. The self is logically prior.
As a matter of direct experience, it's the thing we know with most certainty.
Penrose looks beyond bored here 😂
There is both self or non-self the boundary can be fluid🔥❤️❤️
Hello. We have a semantic cocktail, the I, the self, the me, the my, the double To Be meaning, the tto Stay... Etc.

This is a dumb comment. There are a lot of flaws in Harris’s arguments which are certainly worthy of intellectual engagement. But this is his work. What is egocentric about that? You’re also misunderstanding the concepts of “self” and “ego”. His books aren’t *advising* you to not have an ego.
pedrogibson <----WOOSH

@campesinox just checkout his back and fourth with Noam Chomsky. It is embarassing and Scam behaves like an egocentric spoiled child. Sorry but I think he's BS and scam people with his "products". Thats my opinion. You are free to buy whatever he offers. Peace. Out.
Scam Harris? Really? Get him out of my feed. Thanks. 🙌
Sam Harris? Supporter of genocide?
i think modern people generally get the idea no matter where they from
Penrose isn’t interested in this pseudo-intellectual
I mean we’re all kind of tiptoeing around the fear of nonexistence here. There’s a call to find it. But I’m also called to make scalloped potatoes and sing little songs ya feel

@queserasarahk beautifully put. The hubris of making definitive statements about the unknowable has always struck me as odd and though there’s elements of Sam’s work I think are truly eye opening but it’s the certainty behind what he espouses that always turned me off.

@neilbomb I’m glad you say so. Listening to him always feels like hanging with a friend to me…I like his humor and I’m not lying one day I literally had to use his break glass in case of emergency meditation when I was really low—- but yeah same here, always this little element that made me never quite be able to stick with his work

I have listened to a lot of Sam Harris and still respect Sam Harris. Yet, I feel like most people who are in this niche edge of research about the self also aren’t partnering their philosophy with a dedicated ancestral practice. We can all go sit in a cave and  question the identity of the quantum self, which leads to an ultimate dissolution and ideas and swirls us into the possibility of nothingness. However  I believe the dialogue on being and non-being becomes less fringe and much more grounded when we consider ourselves as part of a living, working tapestry that we can trace throughout the space-time continuum.
